Professional growth
This thing was just copied from other jobs that have clear and quantifiable targets and foisted upon the educators in a copy paste style. The main rationale for its introduction was to appraise teachers’ competence and gauge their desirability for the duty they have undertaken. Its motto is: ‘Enhances Professional Growth and Learning Outcomes’. How it does that remains to be seen.
Those that do not fill out and submit this thing are faced with many threats, including warning letters or withholding of their salaries. We wonder just how the 300,000 people who submit their forms are individually assessed by the commission but it is a time of legacies and everyone would wish to leave a legacy.
We confess lack of knowledge on what a legacy is; but the word is in fashion and the TSC commissioners would like to be praised to their graves for having brought Tpad.
This simple thing that can be done in a few minutes in town is a headache in the marginalised areas. The Tpad day has become like the payday of yore with teachers taking turns to travel to the nearest centre to fill out the form that seems more important than their job.
This is the new heartache and it too shall come to pass. Those that are rooting for it shall go with it or else employ thousands of people just to classify the individual Tpad of every teacher. It will not stay long.



